Desert Ecology

  1. Which two species have, on average, the highest weight? Once you have identified them, make a new column that is a ratio of weight to hindfoot_length. Make a plot that shows the range of this new ratio and fill by sex.
deserts %>% 
  group_by(species) %>% 
  filter(weight!="NA") %>% 
  summarize(mean_weight= mean(weight)) %>% 
  arrange(-mean_weight)

Albigula and Spectabilis

deserts %>% 
  filter(weight!="NA") %>%
  filter(hindfoot_length!="NA") %>% 
  filter(sex!="NA") %>% 
  mutate("weight_to_hindfoot_length" = weight/hindfoot_length ) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=weight_to_hindfoot_length, fill=sex))+
  geom_boxplot()+
  scale_x_log10()+
  labs(title = "Weight to Hindfoot Length Ratio Box Plot",
       x="Weight/Hindfoot Length")+
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = rel(1.5), hjust = 0.5))

  1. Make one plot of your choice! Make sure to include at least two of the aesthetics options you have learned.
deserts %>% 
  filter(species=="flavus") %>% 
  filter(weight!="NA") %>% 
  group_by(year) %>% 
  summarise(avg_weight=mean(weight)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=year, y=avg_weight))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_smooth(method = lm, se = F)+
  labs(title = "Average weight of Flavus Over time",
       x="Year",
       y="Weight")+
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = rel(1.5), hjust = 0.5))
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'
